[[File:Orbitalaltitudes.svg|thumb|To-scale diagram of low, medium and high Earth orbits]] A '''high Earth orbit''' is a [[geocentric orbit]] with an altitude entirely above that of a [[geosynchronous orbit]] ({{convert|35,786|km|mi}}).<ref name=nasa20120718> {{cite web|title=Definitions of geocentric orbits from the Goddard Space Flight Center |url=http://gcmd.nasa.gov/User/suppguide/platforms/orbit.html |work=User support guide: platforms |publisher=NASA Goddard Space Flight Center |accessdate=2012-07-08 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100527132541/http://gcmd.nasa.gov/User/suppguide/platforms/orbit.html |archivedate=2010-05-27 |df= }}</ref> The [[orbital period]]s of such orbits are greater than 24&nbsp;hours, therefore satellites in such orbits have an [[apparent retrograde motion]] – that is, even if they are in a [[prograde motion|prograde]] orbit (90° > [[orbital inclination|inclination]] ≥ 0°), their [[orbital speed|orbital velocity]] is lower than Earth's [[Earth's rotation|rotational]] speed, causing their [[ground track]] to move westward on [[Earth]]'s surface.
